description: Fruiting on a mature cherry tree near our home in Olympia, WA, USA. This same substrate(host tree) has produced fresh fruiting bodies each summer(beginning in mid to late August). Came a bit late this year, but fresh wounds and cut locations on the tree took a bit longer for the mycelium to proliferate(from late winter to September). Images of growth added from initial observation on 9/2/19. Harvested/dehydrated a single small slice for home herbarium/voucher. We have eaten fresh, young slices from this location for the last 2 summers and they are mild and DO indeed taste akin to chicken meat. My experience with the similar species Laetiporus conifericola(fruits on conifers and is far more common here in Washington state) has always been disappointing and the flesh of that species tastes like crushed aspirin(very bitter). The hardwood fruiting sulfur shelf in the midwest(Iowa/Missouri) Laetiporus sulphureus and Laetiporus cincinnatus are mild and taste almost as good as our Laetiporus gilbertsonii.  Link to my MO observation of this collection/monitoring growth-https://mushroomobserver.org/381074?q=w2ax

description:
Chicken of the woods growing on the N side of the trunk of a *Corymbia* (eucalypt) tree; see photo # 6 for image of hist tree leaves. Color yellow. Texture slightly gooey, and the whole thing somewhat springy when knocked on or flicked. Observed on a foggy, dewy morning. Host tree in the parking lot of Casa Bonita Convalescent Hospital, San Dimas, CA. Planning to come back later to harvest it, and probably will warn the hospital staff that their very tall tree will probably fall over soon.. Coin used for scale is a US quarter dollar (¢25 piece), 24.26 mm, 0.955 inch in diameter. 

Update (30 September 2021): Finally got a chance to get back to try to harvest, but alas.. it is too hard and dry now (see photo # 7). I suppose this is a lesson to me, to seize every mushroom like it's your last chance, for it may very well be..

description:
A couple big boys found growing on the S side of a *Eucalyptus* stump near the start of the upper trails in Marshall Canyon, just below Camp Joseph Paige, San Gabriel Mountains foothills. Most of the material was quite hardened and dry, not ripe for harvest, but some was nice and fleshy still. Photo # 3 shows the lower surfaces. Coin used for scale is a US quarter dollar (¢25 piece), 24.26 mm, 0.955 inch in diameter.

Update (evening of the same day): Cooked these bad boys up. Washed well first. Sliced them into thin strips, and pan fried on medium heat in olive oil, with chopped garlic, salt, black pepper, and few squeezes of orange juice. Cooked until well shrunk and starting to crisp. Enjoyed with a Tecate Light with a dash of peach juice. Flavor and texture very much like chicken meat, with just a slight hint of woodiness in a few bites. We shall see later if this, my second, experiment with eating this species goes well or leaves my stomach turned. If this is my last iNat observation, you will have your answer...

description:
Laetiporus gilbertsonii:
Young fruiting on a living weeping Cherry tree.
Almost a month later than prior seasons at this location.
I have monitored/documented annual fruiting of L. gilbertsonii on cherry trees in this same area regularly since 2017.
Harvested a small portion for culinary use. Left the remaining sections to mature.
Dehydrated 2 small sections and bagging for herbarium collection/genetic record.
My coinciding Mushroomobserver observation below-

https://mushroomobserver.org/504129?q=1njN8


UPDATE on 10/6/22: specimens are all thinning/planing/lengthening. Caps orange, pore surface vibrant yellow and nearly at maturity. Uploaded all shots from today(10/6/22). Images 12-19. Harvested a small portion for culinary use.

description:
Large, yellow and pale orange fungi growing on north side of large mature Eucalytus tree. Link to Tasmanian Blue Gum (Eucalyptus globulus) host tree observation: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/137277102

An iNaturalist Introduction to Mushrooming, 6-minute Utube video by Christian Schwartz (leptonia on INat) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LKF_pIY0Zpc

Mushrooms of the Redwood Coast: Comprehensive Guide to the Fungi of Coastal Northern California, Siegel and Schwarz, 2016. p. 472.

California Mushrooms: The Comprehensive Identification Guide, D. Desjardin, M. Wood, and F. Stevens, 2nd printing 2019, p. 389.

Western Hardwood Sulphur Shelf (Laetiporus gilbertsonii)
Fungi of California https://www.mykoweb.com/CAF/species/Laetiporus_gilbertsonii.html
"Common Name: sulphur shelf, chicken of the woods
Misapplied name: Laetiporus sulphureus
Sporocarp: Fruiting body annual; sessile to substipitate, consisting of overlapping, rounded fleshy shelves, 7-55 cm broad, upper surface smooth to roughened, yellow with reddish-orange to orange bands, margin yellow, irregular; flesh 2-3 cm thick, white to yellow; lower surface finely pored, bright yellow; in age fruiting body becoming dry, white and crumbly.
Habitat: Late summer to early fall on logs and stumps of hardwoods. It is particularly common on species of Eucalyptus.
Edible with caution. Prized by many, this species is also known to occasionally cause gastrointestinal upsets. This appears to be caused by eating old and/or insufficiently cooked specimens. If you decide to try it, eat only the young, fresh, growing margins, in small quantities, and cook it thoroughly.
Comments: The brilliant yellow-orange, fleshy shelves of Laetiporus gilbertsonii are unlikely to be mistaken for any other fungus. The sulphur shelf is unusual in that it fruits well before the start of Bay Area rainy season, often in very dry weather. Nonetheless, fruitings, which can be massive, can literally exude moisture. The brightly-colored shelves persist several weeks, then fade to greyish-white, crumble and fall to the ground. Old fruitings on Eucalyptus are frequently infested with termites. Fruitings repeat year after year from the same stump or log.
Our sulphur shelf has long known locally as Laetiporus sulphureus. But we now know that the true L. sulphureus does not occur in the Western United States and that the sulphur shelf that grows on hardwoods in California needs the new name L. gilbertsonii. The sulphur shelf that grows conifers in California is now called Laetiporus conifericola. In the Sierras it is very common on red fir (Abies magnifica).
References
Burdsall Jr., H.H. & Banik, M.T. (2001). The Genus Laetiporus in North America. Harvard Papers in Botany 6: 43-55. (PDF) (Protologue)
Desjardin, D.E., Wood, M.G. & Stevens, F.A. (2015). California Mushrooms: The Comprehensive Identification Guide. Timber Press: Portland, OR. 560 p.
Gilbertson, R.L. (1974). Fungi That Decay Ponderosa Pine. University of Arizona Press: Tuscon, AZ. 197 p.
Gilbertson, R.L. & Ryvarden, L. (1987). North American Polypores, vol. 2. Fungiflora: Oslo, Norway. 452 p.
Ginns, J. (2017). Polypores of British Columbia (Fungi: Basidiomycota). British Columbia: Victoria, BC. 260 p. (PDF)
Overholts, L.O. (1953). The Polyporaceae of the United States, Alaska, and Canada. University of Michigan Press: Ann Arbor, MN. 466 p. (PDF)
Siegel, N. & Schwarz, C. (2016). Mushrooms of the Redwood Coast. Ten Speed Press: Berkeley, CA. 601 p."

description:
This small Western Hardwood Sulfur Shelf mushroom is growing out of the trunk of a Carob Tree, about 10 feet up. There was a more complete mushroom further down the trunk, which I observed separately here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/192295499. It was being eaten by Yellow Cellar Slugs.

I've previously observed 2 of these mushrooms here in the past, so perhaps this is the same colony: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?nelat=33.794708185211&nelng=-117.74926735770939&place_id=any&subview=map&swlat=33.79456329931911&swlng=-117.74943633687732&taxon_id=47170&user_id=kyle_eaton_photography&verifiable=any

description:
Friend sent photo of a yellow fungus for ID. Photo credit: A. Holberg. Link to confirmed observation of Western Hardwood Sulfur nearby: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/137208767

An iNaturalist Introduction to Mushrooming, 6-minute Utube video by Christian Schwartz (leptonia on INat) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LKF_pIY0Zpc

Mushrooms of the Redwood Coast: Comprehensive Guide to the Fungi of Coastal Northern California, Siegel and Schwarz, 2016. p. 472.

California Mushrooms: The Comprehensive Identification Guide, D. Desjardin, M. Wood, and F. Stevens, 2nd printing 2019, p. 389.

Western Hardwood Sulphur Shelf (Laetiporus gilbertsonii)
Fungi of California https://www.mykoweb.com/CAF/species/Laetiporus_gilbertsonii.html
"Common Name: sulphur shelf, chicken of the woods
Misapplied name: Laetiporus sulphureus
Sporocarp: Fruiting body annual; sessile to substipitate, consisting of overlapping, rounded fleshy shelves, 7-55 cm broad, upper surface smooth to roughened, yellow with reddish-orange to orange bands, margin yellow, irregular; flesh 2-3 cm thick, white to yellow; lower surface finely pored, bright yellow; in age fruiting body becoming dry, white and crumbly.
    Habitat: Late summer to early fall on logs and stumps of hardwoods. It is particularly common on species of Eucalyptus.
    Edible with caution. Prized by many, this species is also known to occasionally cause gastrointestinal upsets. This appears to be caused by eating old and/or insufficiently cooked specimens. If you decide to try it, eat only the young, fresh, growing margins, in small quantities, and cook it thoroughly.
    Comments: The brilliant yellow-orange, fleshy shelves of Laetiporus gilbertsonii are unlikely to be mistaken for any other fungus. The sulphur shelf is unusual in that it fruits well before the start of Bay Area rainy season, often in very dry weather. Nonetheless, fruitings, which can be massive, can literally exude moisture. The brightly-colored shelves persist several weeks, then fade to greyish-white, crumble and fall to the ground. Old fruitings on Eucalyptus are frequently infested with termites. Fruitings repeat year after year from the same stump or log.
Our sulphur shelf has long known locally as Laetiporus sulphureus. But we now know that the true L. sulphureus does not occur in the Western United States and that the sulphur shelf that grows on hardwoods in California needs the new name L. gilbertsonii. The sulphur shelf that grows conifers in California is now called Laetiporus conifericola. In the Sierras it is very common on red fir (Abies magnifica).
    References
Burdsall Jr., H.H. & Banik, M.T. (2001). The Genus Laetiporus in North America. Harvard Papers in Botany 6: 43-55. (PDF) (Protologue)
    Desjardin, D.E., Wood, M.G. & Stevens, F.A. (2015). California Mushrooms: The Comprehensive Identification Guide. Timber Press: Portland, OR. 560 p.
    Gilbertson, R.L. (1974). Fungi That Decay Ponderosa Pine. University of Arizona Press: Tuscon, AZ. 197 p.
    Gilbertson, R.L. & Ryvarden, L. (1987). North American Polypores, vol. 2. Fungiflora: Oslo, Norway. 452 p.
    Ginns, J. (2017). Polypores of British Columbia (Fungi: Basidiomycota). British Columbia: Victoria, BC. 260 p. (PDF)
    Overholts, L.O. (1953). The Polyporaceae of the United States, Alaska, and Canada. University of Michigan Press: Ann Arbor, MN. 466 p. (PDF)
    Siegel, N. & Schwarz, C. (2016). Mushrooms of the Redwood Coast. Ten Speed Press: Berkeley, CA. 601 p."
